snippet.textDisplay: There was a time in my life where I could consume around 5-10K calories a day without gaining a pound. Loads of muscle and a raging metabolism. Twenty years later, I have to watch what I eat and can only handle about 3K calories a day without gaining weight. A lot less muscle, but mainly due to allergies that kicked in in my early-twenties that put a major damper on my exercising and outdoor activities. If I ate now like I did in my teens, I would quickly balloon up to 400-500 pounds and most of it being fat lol. I will say that you DON'T need that many calories for weightlifting. I did a lot of weightlifting and a lot of mountain biking when I was eating a lot of calories. I would typically bike for a good 2-3 hours a day and weightlift a good hour a day or every other day. I had plenty of strength and muscle but without the bloated fat belly that a lot of weightlifters seem to get and I attribute it to not overindulging in calories. All you need for good muscle gains is adequate-protein, a good nutrient-filled diet, and water. You don't need any of the gimmicks or voodoo potions a lot of weightlifters claim you need. Eat good, drink good, workout. From my personal experience, I'd have to say that you're going to have one hellova time putting on a lot of muscle without meat. It's not impossible, but a lot more difficult. However, you don't need a LOT of meat.
